            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>What is APR?</h2>
              <p>
                <strong>APR (Annual Percentage Rate)</strong> is the yearly cost
                of borrowing, expressed as a percentage of the amount you
                actually receive. Unlike the simple interest rate, APR includes:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Nominal interest on the loan balance</li>
                <li>
                  Mandatory <strong>upfront fees</strong> (e.g., origination
                  fees, points)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Mandatory <strong>recurring fees</strong> tied to the loan
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Regulators require lenders to disclose APR so that borrowers can
                compare different offers on an apples-to-apples basis.
              </p>

              <h2>APR vs interest rate vs APY</h2>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  <strong>Interest rate:</strong> The base rate charged on the
                  outstanding principal (e.g., 6.5% per year).
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>APR:</strong> The interest rate plus required fees,
                  converted into a single annual rate that matches the actual
                  payment pattern.
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>APY (Annual Percentage Yield):</strong> The effective
                  annual rate earned on savings or investments, including
                  compounding of interest.
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                For loans, APR is the key metric. For savings accounts and
                crypto staking, APY is usually more relevant.
              </p>

              <h2>How this APR calculator works</h2>
              <h3>1. APR from loan details (IRR method)</h3>
              <p>To compute APR from a real-world loan, we:</p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Calculate the periodic payment based on the nominal interest
                  rate, term, and payment frequency.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Build a full schedule of cash flows:
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      At time 0, you receive the loan amount minus any cash-paid
                      fees.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Each period, you pay principal + interest + recurring
                      fees.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use an
                  <strong>internal rate of return (IRR)</strong> calculation on
                  these cash flows to find the periodic rate <code>r</code> that
                  makes the net present value zero.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Convert the periodic rate to an annual APR:
                  <div class="formula-box">
                    <p>
                      Let \( r_p \) be the periodic rate and \( m \) the number
                      of periods per year.
                    </p>
                    <p>Effective APR (including compounding):</p>
                    <p>\[ \text{APR} = \left(1 + r_p\right)^m - 1 \]</p>
                  </div>
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>2. APR from nominal rate & compounding</h3>
              <p>
                If you already know the nominal rate and compounding frequency,
                you can convert between nominal and effective APR using:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  Given nominal rate \( i_{\text{nom}} \) and compounding \( m
                  \) times per year:
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ i_{\text{eff}} = \left(1 +
                  \frac{i_{\text{nom}}}{m}\right)^m - 1 \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  Given effective APR \( i_{\text{eff}} \) and compounding \( m
                  \), the nominal rate is:
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ i_{\text{nom}} = m \left( (1 + i_{\text{eff}})^{1/m} - 1
                  \right) \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Example: Comparing two auto loans</h2>
              <p>
                Suppose you are choosing between two 5-year auto loans for
                $20,000:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Loan A:</strong> 5.9% interest, $800 origination fee,
                  no monthly fee.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Loan B:</strong> 6.5% interest, no origination fee, $5
                  monthly servicing fee.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>By entering each loan into this calculator, you might find:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Loan A APR ≈ 6.7%</li>
                <li>Loan B APR ≈ 7.1%</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Even though Loan A has a higher upfront fee, its lower interest
                rate makes it cheaper overall.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and tips</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  APR assumes you keep the loan for the full term. If you plan
                  to pay it off early, the effective cost may differ.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Some fees (like optional insurance or late fees) are not
                  included in APR by regulation and should not be entered as
                  mandatory fees.
                </li>
                <li>
                  When comparing loans, make sure the
                  <strong>loan type and term</strong> are similar; APR alone is
                  not enough if products are very different.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
              <h3>Does APR include closing costs?</h3>
              <p>
                Some closing costs that are required as a condition of getting
                the loan (for example, certain lender fees) are included in APR.
                Other costs that are more like third‑party services (e.g., title
                insurance, appraisal) may be excluded depending on local
                regulations. Our calculator lets you include any fees you want
                to treat as part of the cost of borrowing.
              </p>

              <h3>Is a lower APR always better?</h3>
              <p>
                Generally yes, if you are comparing similar loans and plan to
                keep them for the full term. However, if one loan has a
                prepayment penalty or other restrictive terms, a slightly higher
                APR with more flexibility might be preferable.
              </p>
